00:06:58.240 --> 00:07:05.840
- Yeah, so the weird bit is this principle

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:07.600
of RESTful interfaces.

00:07:08.020 --> 00:07:10.760
We've all heard of RESTful and we all think we know

00:07:10.840 --> 00:07:13.220
what it means, which is basically something to do

00:07:13.340 --> 00:07:15.960
with a URL structure and return me some JSON

00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:18.860
that gives me the data I need to render my view.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:23.260
Well, if you look at Roy Fielding's original PhD,

00:07:23.700 --> 00:07:26.299
as is brilliantly described in this HTMX article

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:27.900
what I talk about further on down here.

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:29.720
He's not really talking about that stuff.

00:07:29.880 --> 00:07:32.640
Sure, he has some stuff on what the URL structure should be.

00:07:32.680 --> 00:07:36.460
But really, his principle is that the data returned

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:38.940
from the back end should be self-describing,

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:42.200
as in it should have everything you need to go and render

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:42.840
the user interface.

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:46.220
So let's say-- I think they're using the HTMX example

00:07:48.500 --> 00:07:49.220
of a bank account.

00:07:51.080 --> 00:07:54.320
And if you go down to the principle, the long version,

00:07:54.460 --> 00:07:54.820
here we are.

00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:59.540
I've linked to the PhD, but more importantly, the HTMX article, which explains it really well.

00:07:59.920 --> 00:08:04.100
So I think if we follow that, yeah, I think they'll even on that page, he'll have, there's a very,

00:08:04.100 --> 00:08:07.820
they have a jokey tone lots of the time, HTMX, but they also talk about some really cool things.

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:10.780
So somewhere I think they have, yeah, here we are, right?

00:08:11.180 --> 00:08:15.560
So if you look at the traditional JSON response, which I think is the second one,

00:08:18.180 --> 00:08:20.520
and you were trying to show, yeah, right.

00:08:20.680 --> 00:08:24.120
So you and I as humans can read this and be like,

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:25.860
yeah, that kind of explains my bank account

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:26.620
and what's going on.

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:27.720
But there is not enough information.

00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:29.680
It's got like an account number and a balance,

00:08:29.900 --> 00:08:31.960
which is a more complicated object, nested object,

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:33.300
and those types of things.

00:08:33.860 --> 00:08:33.960
Right.

00:08:34.159 --> 00:08:34.740
It's got all the things.

00:08:34.800 --> 00:08:36.099
And we can read account number.

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:36.860
Cool, that's a number.

00:08:37.020 --> 00:08:38.340
Balance, yeah, that makes sense.

00:08:39.519 --> 00:08:41.659
But if you're a computer, there's not enough there

00:08:41.719 --> 00:08:43.500
to go and render someone the nice user interface

00:08:43.659 --> 00:08:46.120
they would want where they would have it displayed on a page.

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:49.019
So if you were the engineering team in the bank

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:53.200
trying to turn this into a web interface,

00:08:53.810 --> 00:08:57.740
you then need to go and have lots of very application-specific

00:08:58.060 --> 00:09:01.560
or page-specific logic to show where the account number goes

00:09:01.610 --> 00:09:03.680
and where the balance goes and where the status goes

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:04.400
and stuff like that.

00:09:05.370 --> 00:09:07.100
And that causes enormous amounts of churn,

00:09:07.110 --> 00:09:09.020
and it means that it's particularly difficult

00:09:09.130 --> 00:09:11.880
for when you have those engineers working in different time zones

00:09:12.210 --> 00:09:14.720
because you end up having this speck between the two.

00:09:14.990 --> 00:09:17.360
And then you always have this problem with software

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:18.720
where, fine, we can get it to work,

00:09:18.840 --> 00:09:20.200
but what happens when we come to add it?

00:09:20.850 --> 00:09:21.840
So what's the process of,

00:09:22.100 --> 00:09:24.680
let's say we want to show as well on this page,

00:09:25.240 --> 00:09:27.820
your like joint account balance,

00:09:28.100 --> 00:09:29.180
let's say just to make something up.

00:09:29.700 --> 00:09:30.620
What we probably need to do

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:31.780
is we need to get the backend guys

00:09:31.910 --> 00:09:34.640
to go and add that to the endpoint

00:09:35.100 --> 00:09:36.040
and then the front end,

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:37.480
and that can be deployed.

00:09:37.550 --> 00:09:39.920
And then the front end can be updated to show that

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:40.760
and the data is available.

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:42.940
That is a lots of churn,

00:09:43.140 --> 00:09:43.980
lots of delay in that.

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:45.180
So the principle-

00:09:45.920 --> 00:09:48.820
It's a coordination between the two domain experts,

00:09:49.150 --> 00:09:51.880
and then you've got that microservice cascading,

00:09:52.100 --> 00:09:55.460
like it's got to do this, then this one's got to be upgraded,

00:09:55.530 --> 00:09:59.640
and then eventually there's enough flow of data through the system

00:09:59.820 --> 00:10:02.160
that the UI people can put it up there, right?

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:02.860
Right.

00:10:03.110 --> 00:10:06.820
And it's bad in this case of showing your bank balance,

00:10:06.930 --> 00:10:08.740
but it gets even worse when you have a form

00:10:09.620 --> 00:10:13.840
where every field in the form needs to be completed, for example.

00:10:14.580 --> 00:10:16.600
And so we basically have to deploy the front end

00:10:16.760 --> 00:10:18.360
that has all of the form components

00:10:18.410 --> 00:10:21.020
and the backend that receives that new form

00:10:21.130 --> 00:10:21.840
at the same time.

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:25.060
And we've got this Pydantic model

00:10:25.260 --> 00:10:27.680
that if we, you know, depending on how we've done it,

00:10:28.160 --> 00:10:29.780
probably is used to define our form

00:10:29.850 --> 00:10:31.980
and it might even be used to define our database.

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:34.420
But like we're not using a Pydantic model

00:10:34.450 --> 00:10:35.240
in the front end.

00:10:35.980 --> 00:10:37.080
TypeScript, in my opinion,

00:10:37.210 --> 00:10:39.840
is a big Achilles heel in typing

00:10:40.020 --> 00:10:40.820
is that you don't have any,

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:42.520
you can't use type hints at runtime.

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:46.340
And so we don't have an equivalent of Pydantic.

00:10:46.510 --> 00:10:48.800
And so we're basically trusting that data is how it is.

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:57.060
And so, yeah, Fast UI is an attempt to basically remove that need

00:10:59.880 --> 00:11:03.320
to have complete synchronization between backend and frontend

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:07.220
by having beautifully designed components in the frontend.

00:11:07.580 --> 00:11:09.220
Not saying what we have now is that beautiful,

00:11:09.330 --> 00:11:10.500
but that's the ideal log term.

00:11:12.660 --> 00:11:15.440
But then the back end can basically just do the orchestration.

00:11:15.580 --> 00:11:18.700
You can say, show me a table, show me a form,

00:11:19.300 --> 00:11:22.460
show me a modal, and put the following content in it, etc.

00:11:24.100 --> 00:11:24.360
Excellent.

00:11:26.180 --> 00:11:27.620
Nice comment from Tony on the audience.

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:30.360
As I originally started in Python, went to use in TypeScript,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.080
Pydantic made the transition back to Python so nice.

00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:38.020
And so in your description, you also have up here

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:41.960
that this Pydantic is involved here.

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:44.040
What is the role that Pydantic plays?

00:11:44.760 --> 00:11:44.880
Right.

00:11:45.310 --> 00:11:51.160
So the idea is that we're getting to this RESTful UI

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:55.040
is really that we end up having a bunch of components

00:11:55.660 --> 00:11:58.320
in a shared definition of some components.

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:00.480
And we basically promise that the backend

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:02.040
is going to send data that matches

00:12:03.300 --> 00:12:05.920
the types defined in the front end.

00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:07.180
Well, that's all very well,

00:12:07.400 --> 00:12:08.160
but if you're not careful,

00:12:08.860 --> 00:12:10.460
you end up not sending quite the right data.

00:12:10.660 --> 00:12:15.200
So what's nice is that all of the components that you can return from FastUI

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:17.820
are themselves Pydantic models.

00:12:18.060 --> 00:12:21.540
And so Pydantic goes off and does not only the validation,

00:12:21.880 --> 00:12:24.780
but also the coercion, and it does stuff like uses camel case

00:12:25.180 --> 00:12:28.540
so that front-end developers are happy because we've got no underscores anywhere.

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:34.560
And so, yeah, all of the front-end, sorry, the backend code for FastUI

00:12:34.700 --> 00:12:38.720
is basically just Pydantic models, which implement these,

00:12:41.220 --> 00:12:42.760
implement these components, right?

00:12:43.180 --> 00:12:45.900
So it might be useful for those who can see this to go in

00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:49.600
and I can talk through an example if we go into the code here

