00:13:18.590 --> 00:13:20.160
which is the text you would put within the button.

00:13:20.940 --> 00:13:23.020
Then it contains the event that you want to fire

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:24.120
when someone clicks on it.

00:13:25.480 --> 00:13:26.740
And HTML type,

00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:30.100
which in this matches what you can get in HTML,

00:13:30.880 --> 00:13:32.020
button, reset, submit,

00:13:32.580 --> 00:13:33.840
and then class name,

00:13:34.120 --> 00:13:36.120
which becomes the classes that get applied.

00:13:36.330 --> 00:13:38.880
And then critically this type, which is a literal,

00:13:38.950 --> 00:13:39.820
which has to be button.

00:13:40.350 --> 00:13:44.520
And that is used by the discriminated union in Pydantic

00:13:44.610 --> 00:13:47.060
to do the validation of different types.

00:13:47.170 --> 00:13:49.720
And it's also used by a big switch statement

00:13:49.990 --> 00:13:52.260
in the TypeScript to basically decide

00:13:53.220 --> 00:13:54.600
what component I'll go and render

00:13:54.740 --> 00:13:56.760
when I get back an object.

00:13:58.280 --> 00:13:59.900
Right, so there's some TypeScript.

00:14:00.380 --> 00:14:05.680
Maybe it makes sense to talk a bit about the building blocks.

00:14:05.860 --> 00:14:07.800
So you say FastUI is made up of four things.

00:14:08.490 --> 00:14:11.800
Just so people can get a sense of like, what's at play here?

00:14:12.640 --> 00:14:12.760
Right.

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:18.340
So the four things that we have now are a PyPy package, a Python package called FastUI,

00:14:18.680 --> 00:14:21.040
which I was just showing you there the types for.

00:14:21.420 --> 00:14:26.240
And then we have a npm package called FastUI.

00:14:26.350 --> 00:14:28.180
Again, it's in the Pydantic organization.

00:14:30.180 --> 00:14:33.860
which is where the meat of the logic resides

00:14:33.860 --> 00:14:35.500
and that's implementing basically

00:14:36.760 --> 00:14:40.680
most of the components and all of the wiring

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:42.140
to mean that when I return a button,

00:14:43.100 --> 00:14:44.800
the button component gets rendered.

00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:48.820
But obviously, we don't probably want to end up

00:14:48.860 --> 00:14:52.560
using a vanilla button when we come to display it.

00:14:52.680 --> 00:14:56.499
So then I've implemented basically customization

00:14:56.500 --> 00:14:59.220
of the FastUI React library using Bootstrap.

00:14:59.600 --> 00:15:01.380
So all that's really doing is it's deciding

00:15:01.400 --> 00:15:05.420
what classes to append to use with each component

00:15:05.720 --> 00:15:07.240
and also just customizing a few of them.

00:15:07.240 --> 00:15:08.120
So for example, modal,

00:15:08.680 --> 00:15:10.520
there's no like nice way to do a vanilla modal.

00:15:10.700 --> 00:15:14.700
So the modal implementation in the default FastUI npm package

00:15:15.340 --> 00:15:17.660
just basically shows me alert saying this isn't implemented,

00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:20.460
whereas the Bootstrap one uses a nice Bootstrap modal.

00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:24.060
And then we have finally FastUI pre-built,

00:15:24.300 --> 00:15:28.020
which basically uses the Fast UI package,

00:15:28.620 --> 00:15:30.040
customizes it with Fast UI Bootstrap,

00:15:30.410 --> 00:15:31.620
and then builds it.

00:15:31.780 --> 00:15:35.620
And that means we can go and basically return

00:15:36.300 --> 00:15:37.900
that pre-built React app

00:15:38.290 --> 00:15:39.780
without having to get our hands dirty

00:15:39.960 --> 00:15:44.460
with npm on Yarn and Vite and all the other...

00:15:44.560 --> 00:15:47.060
All the webpacky bundling,

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:50.420
minifying, transpiling business.

00:15:51.760 --> 00:15:53.820
But the cool bit, in my opinion,

00:15:54.240 --> 00:15:56.060
of fast UI is that at its core,

00:15:56.110 --> 00:15:59.080
it's really the definition of a bunch of different

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:01.780
schemas effectively.

00:16:02.270 --> 00:16:04.360
The schemas are defined in Pydantic

00:16:04.560 --> 00:16:05.680
and they're defined in TypeScript,

00:16:06.900 --> 00:16:08.720
but they could perfectly well be,

00:16:10.420 --> 00:16:12.860
and really nicely, I just merged this the other day,

00:16:12.980 --> 00:16:15.940
we now use the JSON schema generated by Pydantic

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:21.440
and JSON schema generated by the React types

00:16:21.820 --> 00:16:23.679
to basically go and test

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:25.180
that there's an equivalence between those two,

00:16:25.500 --> 00:16:26.140
those models everywhere.

00:16:26.740 --> 00:16:28.440
But in theory, there's nothing to stop the front end

00:16:28.490 --> 00:16:30.780
from being built with another JavaScript library

00:16:30.960 --> 00:16:33.660
or even with something like HTML and HTMX,

00:16:34.340 --> 00:16:37.080
or even you could go and use React Native and build,

00:16:38.240 --> 00:16:40.220
or even some kind of embedded device.

00:16:40.330 --> 00:16:41.880
You could go and implement those components.

00:16:42.450 --> 00:16:44.520
And then on the other side, and this is even more achievable,

00:16:45.160 --> 00:16:49.359
you could go and return data that matches those models

00:16:49.380 --> 00:16:53.100
from a Rust or Go service.

00:16:53.720 --> 00:16:55.620
And in theory, you don't have to change your UI at all

00:16:55.860 --> 00:16:57.200
because all you're doing is I promise

00:16:57.380 --> 00:16:59.140
that I'm gonna match these schemas

00:16:59.780 --> 00:17:02.820
and then whatever front end or whatever back end

00:17:03.360 --> 00:17:04.240
can then communicate.

00:17:04.480 --> 00:17:06.640
Whether that comes to pass, I don't know yet.

00:17:06.720 --> 00:17:09.819
And obviously I built the default back end in Python

00:17:09.900 --> 00:17:10.819
'cause that's what I know best

00:17:10.839 --> 00:17:12.459
and where I think Pyntic's really helpful.

00:17:13.419 --> 00:17:17.060
And I built the first front end in React and TypeScript

00:17:17.300 --> 00:17:18.259
'cause one, that's what I know

00:17:18.280 --> 00:17:19.900
and two, it's what we're using within Pydantic.

00:17:20.079 --> 00:17:23.459
But lots of people have asked about HTMX.

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:27.140
People have also asked about Svelte and others.

00:17:27.439 --> 00:17:31.500
I think I wouldn't see the point in building a fast UI in Vue

00:17:31.780 --> 00:17:33.140
because I don't think it adds much.

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:34.040
It's just a lot of work.

00:17:34.440 --> 00:17:39.140
But I think there's a world where we build a HTMX template rendered version

00:17:39.660 --> 00:17:42.300
of fast UI's front end that could be super valuable.

00:17:43.560 --> 00:17:44.040
That's interesting.

00:17:44.700 --> 00:17:51.500
So first point is these different components sound like they are potentially a little mix and match.

00:17:51.790 --> 00:17:54.220
You know, you could take it all as one big thing, or you could say,

00:17:54.740 --> 00:18:00.300
really like the way it defines the React front end, but we're going to implement it some other endpoint.

00:18:01.880 --> 00:18:06.820
Yeah, I think it's something like it'll be slightly skewed now because of tests,

00:18:07.040 --> 00:18:12.040
but I'd say it's sort of twice as much front end to back end at the moment,

00:18:12.280 --> 00:18:15.240
as in the, yeah, it's skewed a bit by tests,

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:16.540
but even now there's more TypeScript.

00:18:17.020 --> 00:18:18.980
So I think the simplest thing to do,

00:18:19.140 --> 00:18:20.700
and you could do it pretty trivially,

00:18:20.800 --> 00:18:22.060
would be to use another backend,

00:18:24.539 --> 00:18:26.820
another language for your backend service.

00:18:27.340 --> 00:18:29.260
And as long as it matches those types,

00:18:29.400 --> 00:18:31.520
and you could even go and use something like JSON Schema

00:18:31.660 --> 00:18:32.320
to enforce that.

00:18:34.519 --> 00:18:37.860
But yeah, re-implementing the front end,

00:18:38.020 --> 00:18:40.020
probably a bigger piece of work, but totally doable.

00:18:40.220 --> 00:18:42.440
I mean, I did it in my spare time in two weeks,

00:18:42.470 --> 00:18:43.080
got the whole thing.

00:18:43.090 --> 00:18:45.700
So it's not millions of different things.

00:18:45.840 --> 00:18:47.340
There's kind of 20 components at the moment

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:48.760
that are then composable to build

00:18:49.220 --> 00:18:51.300
reasonably sophisticated like UIs.

00:18:53.700 --> 00:18:55.980
- So this is a web front end

00:18:57.960 --> 00:19:00.720
like Flask or Django sort of framework,

00:19:01.520 --> 00:19:04.080
but a way that really incorporates building the UI

00:19:04.430 --> 00:19:08.359
in Python and validating and enforcing it with Pydantic

00:19:08.380 --> 00:19:11.660
rather than just, hey, file new HTML.

00:19:12.060 --> 00:19:14.080
Let's just start typing and hope they line up.

00:19:14.660 --> 00:19:16.880
You know, like instead of trying to juggle

00:19:16.920 --> 00:19:19.540
all those different languages, CSS, HTML,

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:22.320
all the JavaScript tooling for packing up stuff,

00:19:22.960 --> 00:19:24.440
just let's write Python, right?

00:19:24.500 --> 00:19:28.080
So maybe you got a simple example of what it looks like

00:19:28.100 --> 00:19:33.660
to define a real simple example here on the readme.

00:19:34.240 --> 00:19:46.620
It's got a very interesting parity between what is in the HTML DOM and what is in the Python abstract syntax tree, I guess.

00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:49.260
And visually as well.

00:19:49.280 --> 00:19:53.080
The way you look at the code, it looks like the way it might look in HTML.

00:19:53.520 --> 00:19:57.360
Give us a sense of what writing a UI in this would look like.

00:19:58.080 --> 00:19:58.240
Right.

00:19:58.360 --> 00:20:02.940
So I think first of all, we have to talk about the two most obvious pitfalls for this.

00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:13.280
One end of the pitfall you have, which I think is the biggest temptation, is to basically mirror all of HTML in Python.

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:18.120
And for those of us who are happy writing HTML or writing React, that sounds like hell.

00:20:18.360 --> 00:20:29.860
It's going to be slow because you have to do some weird rendering, but it's also just going to be a pig because I don't want to have to define every A, Href, and everything else in Python code.

00:20:32.520 --> 00:20:34.780
it requires for start requires you to know two things,

00:20:35.020 --> 00:20:37.220
Python and HTML, whereas to write HTML,

00:20:37.300 --> 00:20:38.300
you only need to know one.

00:20:39.500 --> 00:20:39.560
Yeah.

00:20:39.560 --> 00:20:42.020
And I also, I always find these things that try to dodge,

00:20:42.220 --> 00:20:45.000
like dodge the fact that HTML exists.

00:20:45.960 --> 00:20:48.560
I find them, I just, they don't resonate with me.

00:20:48.700 --> 00:20:50.140
I'm not entirely sure why.

00:20:50.360 --> 00:20:53.120
It's like we have really nice things like CSS

00:20:53.700 --> 00:20:55.220
and we have really,

00:20:55.820 --> 00:20:59.040
there's just so much tooling and frameworks,

00:20:59.800 --> 00:21:02.400
you know, you mentioned Brutestrap already, right?

00:21:02.500 --> 00:21:03.540
that just plug into there.

00:21:03.540 --> 00:21:05.420
And if it's like, well, we're just going to write,

00:21:06.380 --> 00:21:07.280
recreate it in Python.

00:21:07.520 --> 00:21:09.520
Well, it has all the oddities of HTML

00:21:09.700 --> 00:21:12.160
if it's going to be really high parity.

00:21:12.480 --> 00:21:15.120
And then you just have a less well-known way

00:21:15.180 --> 00:21:16.260
to do the same weird thing.

00:21:16.480 --> 00:21:16.760
I don't know.

00:21:17.340 --> 00:21:18.620
It doesn't resonate super with me.

00:21:19.040 --> 00:21:19.460
I agree.

00:21:19.560 --> 00:21:22.120
And I found the same thing at times with ORMs

00:21:22.380 --> 00:21:24.660
that you end up, the worst case of an ORM

00:21:24.760 --> 00:21:26.320
is you work out what you need to do in SQL.

00:21:27.120 --> 00:21:29.520
Then you try and translate back from SQL to ORM.

00:21:30.200 --> 00:21:31.539
And it would be much nicer

00:21:31.560 --> 00:21:32.460
just to write my SQL.

00:21:32.570 --> 00:21:33.320
I mean, not always the case.

00:21:33.460 --> 00:21:34.320
ORMs can be powerful,

00:21:34.430 --> 00:21:36.360
but I think that they both can fall

00:21:36.530 --> 00:21:38.600
into the same trap if you're not careful.

00:21:39.520 --> 00:21:40.040
And then I was going to say

00:21:40.070 --> 00:21:41.120
at the far end of the spectrum,

00:21:41.200 --> 00:21:42.020
the other end of the spectrum,

00:21:42.190 --> 00:21:45.960
you have, and I guess Django's admin view

00:21:46.030 --> 00:21:46.880
for understandable reasons

00:21:47.140 --> 00:21:47.820
could suffer from this,

00:21:47.940 --> 00:21:49.560
that you basically have a very small set of things.

00:21:49.590 --> 00:21:52.380
You have a table page and a details page

00:21:52.920 --> 00:21:54.540
and a form page, and that's kind of it, right?

00:21:54.800 --> 00:21:56.460
So there's this difficult trade-off

00:21:56.640 --> 00:21:57.880
and where in that continuum

00:21:58.100 --> 00:21:59.979
do we try to choose

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:01.840
what size of component to implement, right?

00:22:01.980 --> 00:22:04.380
So for example, here we have a heading,

00:22:04.780 --> 00:22:06.640
which is almost one-for-one matches

00:22:07.100 --> 00:22:07.960
what you would do in HTML.

00:22:08.260 --> 00:22:10.060
We have the text that goes within it

00:22:10.060 --> 00:22:10.840
and we have the level,

00:22:11.120 --> 00:22:12.900
which, you know, it's slightly different syntax,

00:22:13.200 --> 00:22:16.560
but it's basically one-for-one matching an HTML tag.

00:22:17.060 --> 00:22:18.340
But then we have a table,

00:22:19.360 --> 00:22:22.620
which it doesn't look very much like an HTML table at all.

00:22:22.660 --> 00:22:24.820
We're not having to explicitly define

00:22:25.540 --> 00:22:27.360
the table body versus the table head.

00:22:27.540 --> 00:22:28.780
We're not having to put in each column.

00:22:29.480 --> 00:22:30.300
We're not having to worry.

00:22:30.760 --> 00:22:33.380
Yeah, there's lots of stuff here that is much less like it.

00:22:33.380 --> 00:22:37.940
And that's where it's in these very common components

00:22:38.280 --> 00:22:41.120
where there is consistent things that lots of people want to do

00:22:41.450 --> 00:22:43.620
or lots of places in your app where you might want to do them,

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:47.620
where I think a framework like Fast UI gets super powerful

00:22:47.850 --> 00:22:53.540
because we can get you a table here with users defined

00:22:53.860 --> 00:22:55.800
and with a few columns with some customization

00:22:56.070 --> 00:22:58.740
on what happens when you, how we render each column.

00:22:59.160 --> 00:23:02.140
much more quickly than we could go write out all the HTML for that.

00:23:02.900 --> 00:23:04.460
And it's much more concise to read.

00:23:06.580 --> 00:23:10.320
It's consistent enough that something like GitHub Copilot

00:23:10.350 --> 00:23:13.780
will help you write it out where you do have a bit of customization to do.

00:23:14.150 --> 00:23:16.100
I think this is where it can be super powerful.

00:23:17.200 --> 00:23:18.400
It is pretty interesting.

00:23:18.720 --> 00:23:19.560
I like the hierarchy.

00:23:20.940 --> 00:23:25.340
For people listening, just check out github.com/pydanix slash fast UI.

00:23:25.750 --> 00:23:26.920
The example right there on the page.

00:23:27.520 --> 00:23:38.720
But what you do is you create, in this case, a FastAPI endpoint, and then you return a hierarchy of elements out of fast UI.

00:23:38.780 --> 00:23:39.800
So we have a page.

00:23:40.040 --> 00:23:41.040
The page has components.

00:23:41.200 --> 00:23:43.960
The components are a list of a header and a table.

00:23:44.500 --> 00:23:56.460
The table has data, which maps over to a list of Pydantic models, which then helps say what goes in the field for the column headings and things like that.

00:23:57.140 --> 00:23:58.260
It's pretty interesting.

00:23:58.930 --> 00:23:59.600
I think it's neat.

00:24:01.240 --> 00:24:01.720
Yeah, thank you.

00:24:01.930 --> 00:24:03.360
And obviously we can add other components

00:24:03.560 --> 00:24:04.840
like pagination that works.

00:24:05.090 --> 00:24:06.700
I think just to come back to the top

00:24:06.900 --> 00:24:08.220
to how we do these views,

00:24:09.110 --> 00:24:11.320
the very simple and it's most simple

00:24:11.480 --> 00:24:14.000
what FastUI's React app does

00:24:14.540 --> 00:24:16.820
is it basically takes whatever the URL is you go to.

00:24:16.960 --> 00:24:19.600
So in this case, you might go to slash to the base URL

00:24:20.300 --> 00:24:22.600
and it prepends slash API

00:24:23.620 --> 00:24:25.479
and makes a request to that endpoint

00:24:25.480 --> 00:24:27.500
to basically say, what should I render?

00:24:28.040 --> 00:24:28.840
And it gets back.

00:24:29.060 --> 00:24:32.720
So here we're basically returning a list of Pydantic models.

00:24:33.380 --> 00:24:36.180
All that the FastUI model is really doing

00:24:36.300 --> 00:24:37.780
is taking that list of Pydantic models

00:24:38.380 --> 00:24:41.160
and calling model dump JSON on it

00:24:41.460 --> 00:24:44.540
to get the JSON that we return to the front end.

00:24:45.100 --> 00:24:48.020
As I say, the front end then knows how to render

00:24:48.900 --> 00:24:51.320
each of those, each dictionary in the list

00:24:51.360 --> 00:24:52.240
is what it is at its core.

00:24:52.500 --> 00:24:56.520
At its core, it's a list of objects to use JavaScript parlance,

00:24:57.180 --> 00:24:59.080
and it just knows how to render each of them,

00:24:59.090 --> 00:25:00.500
and it renders each of them in turn.

00:25:00.840 --> 00:25:04.400
And then, obviously, they can then have nested other models,

00:25:04.520 --> 00:25:06.160
all of which it knows how to render.

00:25:06.880 --> 00:25:07.540
Yeah, absolutely.

00:25:08.680 --> 00:25:10.260
It reminds me of a couple of things.

00:25:11.660 --> 00:25:12.540
I have an example.

00:25:12.860 --> 00:25:13.320
Is this? No?

00:25:13.580 --> 00:25:14.080
Somewhere along here.

00:25:14.080 --> 00:25:14.560
I pulled it up.

00:25:15.240 --> 00:25:19.400
It reminds me of kind of what React looks like.

00:25:19.500 --> 00:25:20.240
People have done React.

00:25:20.660 --> 00:25:26.320
You know, you write a function that returns kind of an HTML thing,

00:25:26.460 --> 00:25:30.060
but then it has JavaScript arrow functions, right?

00:25:32.360 --> 00:25:34.200
But it has the same nested feel, right?

00:25:34.800 --> 00:25:38.300
Did React inspire you to create it this way or not really?

00:25:38.680 --> 00:25:39.380
Yeah, it did.

00:25:39.480 --> 00:25:42.200
I've done quite a lot of React, and I like it a lot.

00:25:42.340 --> 00:25:48.940
I know as a popular piece of technology, there are lots of people who like to berate it,

00:25:49.080 --> 00:25:51.620
but I do think React has been a powerful step forward.

00:25:51.820 --> 00:25:55.320
And the greatest form of flattery is copying.

00:25:55.880 --> 00:25:57.180
And there are enough other,

00:25:57.420 --> 00:25:58.960
like sure there are other more powerful,

00:25:59.520 --> 00:26:00.260
arguably more powerful,

00:26:00.560 --> 00:26:02.980
arguably more performant new front-end libraries,

00:26:03.180 --> 00:26:05.340
but everything is component-based now.

00:26:05.740 --> 00:26:09.160
Like React has changed the sea change

00:26:09.160 --> 00:26:11.920
in how we did front-end with their component architecture.

00:26:12.220 --> 00:26:14.440
And JSX similarly is super powerful.

00:26:15.740 --> 00:26:17.980
So one of the things that I think we're going to get to,

00:26:18.060 --> 00:26:18.960
I don't want to dive into it yet,

00:26:19.060 --> 00:26:28.360
But like in React, you would say like, we're going to return a photo context or a switch or something that is not typically known in HTML.

00:26:28.440 --> 00:26:31.760
And these are higher order building blocks in the UI space, right?

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:41.800
So when people think about what they're creating here in Python, it's not just the fundamental DOM objects and elements, is it?

00:26:42.420 --> 00:26:42.520
Right.

00:26:42.580 --> 00:26:43.960
So that's exactly, yeah.

00:26:44.100 --> 00:26:46.380
So page here is a bit of ambiguity

00:26:46.580 --> 00:26:47.880
about how we're going to define a page.

00:26:48.560 --> 00:26:51.480
Like default implementation does something reasonably sensible.

